Bakal&#39;s tenant: Drowning in the stove, he signed a higher rent
An older stocky man walked out the door of the RPG Byty &quot;uhlobarona&quot; client center of Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rental apartments in the Czech Republic.
He carried a folder under his arm and new leases in it for three apartments: his, his daughter and his son, who is serving his sentence.
It was deregulation that raised rents for all three.
Instead of 3,500 a month, the son will pay 4,100 crowns for a 2 + 1 apartment in the second category from next year.
&quot;And it&#39;s not hot water there, and petrama must be drowning,&quot; the man points his finger at his son&#39;s new contract, for the signing of which he has a power of attorney.
&quot;But I signed it,&quot; he explains, half angry and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new lease conditions as &quot;incorrect and immoral,&quot; advises tenants not to sign new contracts and wait until December 7, when they will publish instructions on how to proceed against them.
But the man just waves his hand over it.
&quot;One says it, the other it,&quot; he frowns.
The Ostrava region is becoming a large laboratory of deregulation.
After the New Year, the vast majority of flats that have non-market rents in the Czech Republic await.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit the &quot;laboratory&quot; in person.
The Havířov RPG waiting room is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already full at 9 am on Tuesday.
Right next to the door is a security guard from a security agency with a call device.
&quot;Rent 2011&quot;, a special button on its touch screen lights up.
One tap and a numbered piece of paper comes out of the machine.
You can&#39;t even read &quot;157&quot; and your digit is already beeping on the large display under the waiting room ceiling.
It&#39;s your turn in half a second.
An elderly couple comes to ask about the rent after a while, but the rush in the waiting room obviously does not apply to the new rents at all.
Most people came to solve common problems as usual - requests for repairs, insurance claims and the like.
In the Ostrava region, tenants of most of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio have been receiving letters with new leases in their mailboxes since about mid-November.
RPG Apartments in the letters suggests to them to increase the rent by 15 to 38 percent.
A special counter for new leases was opened at the client center on 18 November.
&quot;It&#39;s been running for over a week, so it&#39;s only in the running-down,&quot; the workers behind the counter answer after a moment&#39;s hesitation as the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakal&#39;s former mining apartments are a local hot topic.
Before the election, the Deputy Speaker of Parliament and a native of Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek from the CSSD, took him in quite aloud, and even now the local newspaper is full of him.
&quot;Twenty years later, I want a new floor.&quot;
&quot;They didn&#39;t even change the board in the toilet,&quot; the man mentioned at the beginning is relieved.
Most of the time, according to employees, retirees come to see if they will receive a rental discount if they sign in time, as the RPG promises in a special offer.
Half of the discount on the February rent will also be given to other tenants who sign a new contract by 15 December.
However, Havířov&#39;s &quot;deregulation&quot; counter is definitely not overwhelmed by questions.
&quot;Of yesterday&#39;s 360 clients, only about forty to fifty people were here because of the 2011 lease,&quot; the workers estimate behind the counter.
At the same time, the RPG suggests individual contracting on the website and on its bulletin boards where necessary.
However, if both parties do not agree on the lease, it will have to be determined by an independent court.
&quot;This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal procedure,&quot; RPG warns on its website.
&quot;No one will be judged here,&quot; thinks one of the RPG Apartments flats, and the man on the street in front of the client center partially agrees.
&quot;I have a 13,000 pension and I have five thousand left to eat, I don&#39;t have to judge,&quot; he says.
But then the worker is still uncertain.
&quot;We&#39;ll see.&quot;
&quot;Mr. Zaorálek tells them in the media not to sign, so people are probably waiting,&quot; he thinks.
The regulation of rents ends in most of the Czech Republic with the New Year 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, their increase is an economic necessity.
&quot;The current rent still does not even reach the amount necessary for simple maintenance of the housing stock,&quot; reminds Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, that the neglect of the housing stock blamed on the angry tenant is the main reason for the increase in rents.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPGs could invest four billion in rents in apartments, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling opposite the upholstered seats of the Havířov waiting room so far repeats some information highlighted in red.
&quot;The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% or less applies to 31,200 apartments, which is more than 90% of RPG apartments.&quot;
&quot;And it will always be a maximum of CZK 7.50 per square meter per month,&quot; appears on the screen.
Only for 400 apartments from the RPG portfolio, the rent will increase by 38 percent.
&quot;In these cases, it is an increase from the extremely low amount of CZK 19.66 per square meter,&quot; points out RPG.
For 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain the same next year.
RPG Apartments promises that deregulation will not drive out rents by leaps and bounds, but will be spread over four to eight years.
In addition, it adds another commitment: all the money from the increase in rent (see chart) will be returned by the company to the apartments, mainly to heat savings - new windows and insulation.
They should be given priority to people who sign a rent increase agreement.
The kindergarten also belongs to the offices, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect her to hide a mini-kindergarten with everything that goes with it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a pile of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
From October last year, it can be visited by children of Arch.Design employees.
The design-architectural company Arch.Design, from whose studios a number of important Brno buildings emerged, has been counting on space for its company mini-kindergarten since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
She employs almost 90 people, mostly in the baby boom age, and she cared about the women designers and architects being able to return to work quickly.
Together with the possibility of part-time work, the kindergarten is a benefit that Arch.Design offers to its employees within the social program.
Builders thus have the opportunity to combine demanding work with child care.
The mini-kindergarten was invented by the employees of Arch.Design themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs.
The company&#39;s mini-kindergarten is financed from the European Social Fund through the Operational Program Human Resources and Employment and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant financing (subsidies in the amount of CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and facilities and provide qualified staff and operations for a period of two years.
After the financial subsidy has been used up (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate a mini-kindergarten at its own expense for a period of 3 years.
The preparation of the project took one year and Economy Rating significantly helped with the application for the subsidy.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are cared for all day by a nurse and kindergarten teacher, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are older than 3 years.
Because it is a &quot;mini-kindergarten&quot;, only 5 children can be present at a time, but even more will take turns during the day.
The operation of the kindergarten is flexible according to the needs of parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the hierarchy of position in the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the program content in the mini-kindergarten is comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation for school desks, English is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time, and stressful situations with delayed collection of children from kindergartens far from the parents&#39; workplace are eliminated.
Parents use working time more productively.
No wonder a naturally loyal employee-employer relationship is established here.
Arch.Design thus became one of the Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and have strengthened personnel marketing through this program.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look at Gaudí&#39;s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the backbone of a dinosaur and the balconies are open fish mouths.
Such is the Casa Batlló in Barcelona by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the house has earned the nickname House of Bones from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and ubiquitous soft curves are all typical of Antoni Gaudí&#39;s Art Nouveau.
The facade of the house is played with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures reminiscent of nature and animals.
Detailed observation shows geometry, rhythm and precisely thought-out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house sounds even more dramatic, it is illuminated so that the impression of the gloss of the colors is further enhanced.
Winding and twisting of shapes equally occurs in interiors.
Wood in the waves copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and moldings.
The Batlló House, located in the Eixample district on the lively 43 shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, was rebuilt in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but soon accepted Gaudí&#39;s idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment building himself.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated with him.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of mosaics on the facade.
Many other creators and artists also worked on the facade.
Working together on the designs of Casa Batlló started Jujol&#39;s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol was involved in the construction of Gaudí&#39;s Casa Milá and Güell Park, which contains Gaudí&#39;s other works.
Due to its organic shapes, the house earned the nickname &quot;House of Bones&quot; from the locals soon after its completion.
Others began to call it a &quot;yawning house&quot; due to its specific window-opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted on top of the building.
Hidden religious motifs also contain other sculptural elements of the building.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system for the house with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Their forty-five degree inclination may seem bizarre.
In Gaudí&#39;s work, he absolutely did not respect the building regulations of the time and did not allow himself to be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later, when completed, the city council was terrified by the result and asked for redress.
The councilors were annoyed, for example, that the building also interfered with the pillars in the public sidewalk.
There was never a remedy, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the district&#39;s call, Josep Batlló applied for (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two top floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon and on the third floor there was a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The whole six-storey house is intersected by a staircase that leads to the ascent to the roof terrace.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement by curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the lounge door, and a larger company can communicate comfortably with each other without retaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
In addition to the new façade, the house with Gaudí&#39;s reconstruction also received an unconventional roof and two extra floors.
Gaudí&#39;s play with light, blue and white glazed tiles, which line the inner courtyard, and skylights is also impressive.
The play of two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which absorbs the sun&#39;s rays.
Casa Batlló, a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2005, is well worth a visit.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and magnificent apartment open to the public.
The owners decided to take this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the celebrations of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous artist.
They stayed on the tours, as they found it to be a very profitable business, and in addition they expanded the tours to include common and attic spaces, including a roof terrace.
Admission to the monument is definitely not negligible, it is 16.50 euros and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist passes have a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of a house with dragon turrets, you have to quickly make friends with one of the inhabitants of the apartment building and visit him right at home.
How to choose a mattress and slat: women have different requirements than men
Not the ostentatious frame of the bed, but the quality of the lying area, ie the mattress and the slat, give the basis of a really good bed.
However, they must be harmoniously complemented to suit a particular user.
When choosing, many things decide, from the weight, height, age, health and gender of the owner.
The type of interior into which the mattress and slatted frame are purchased is also important.
A typical example?
For example, latex mattresses are not suitable for weekend cottages, where they do not heat regularly, because they &quot;heat up&quot; more slowly.
In addition, they tend to weigh significantly more than standard polyurethane mattresses.
At the same time, it is usually necessary to turn them regularly.
If they don&#39;t have a lot of vent channels in the core, and they still lie on a solid board, they retain moisture: Mold could also appear under them.
Habit also decides when choosing.
Anyone who has spent a long time abroad, where very high mattresses with a softening layer are often used, will hardly feel good on a low and hard surface.
&quot;Perhaps all the hockey players returning from the NHL have complained to me that they will not sleep here.&quot;
&quot;They needed mattresses with a softening layer of lazy foam for their battered shoulders, heels and hips.&quot;
&quot;Such is also recommended, for example, for people with diabetes who have a disorder of the nervous system, so they do not receive well, information&quot; from the joints and skin, &quot;explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
For many hockey players, but also for other customers, years ago, she was looking for mattresses with lazy foam years ago.
&quot;Today it&#39;s fine, Tempur, Italian Magniflex, but also Czech Tropico have suitable mattresses.&quot;
You don&#39;t have to be an NHL guy to appreciate lazy foam.
This &quot;miracle&quot; works simply.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape according to the absorbed heat or adapts to your warm body.
Nothing pushes you, you won&#39;t roll over at night like after a hard match.
You just sleep better.
Lazy foam also acts as a protection against bedsores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add the length of the foot to your height, which is usually about 21 to 34 cm.
Both men and women with a height of about 180 cm need a bed of 210 to 220 cm.
The minimum width for one should be 90 cm for a double bed, ie a total of 180 cm.
For single beds, such as singles, at least 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
For convenience and a possible visit.
&quot;Otherwise, the rule for the width of the bed is simple: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably slightly bent at the elbow,&quot; advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, guildmaster of the Guild of Upholsterers and Decorators, who has been dealing with the issue of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for many years and lectures at vocational schools.
For a double bed, everyone needs their own slatted frame and mattress, but be careful when shopping to match the height of the mattress.
Otherwise, all you have to do is mount the slats at different heights, but you may not be able to do that with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should have a height of at least 14 cm, types with a spring frame at least 15, of which at least three centimeters should count on the shaping and loosening layer.
&quot;When touching your hands or landing on a mattress, you definitely must not feel the springs,&quot; warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of grate.
Fully upholstered beds, where the mattress and the base are like fused Siamese twins, have nothing to do in the bedrooms.
The mattresses are poorly ventilated, their cover cannot be washed, which is already common today.
And because we normally sweat 0.2 to 0.75 liters of sweat at night, it is clear that after five to seven years the mattress will start to resemble one large (and clogged) sieve.
That is why experts reject advertising slogans about the life of mattresses up to 25 years, or even lifetime warranties.
But everything has its but.
And that&#39;s why practical advice from dealers: for mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, do not give up the hygiene and washable cover, but rather add a mattress protector that you can easily remove and wash.
Although mattress covers with zippers are commonly produced around the entire perimeter today, so after opening we get two parts (very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), Handling with larger types (and with one person) could still resemble a light weight duel in the ring with a heavy.
Do you have a fixed board in bed instead of a grate?
Never!
Maximum for a one-night bed.
However, provide the board (if it does not already have it) with ventilation openings and use a mattress with a spring frame and a height of at least 15 cm with springs in bags (of which Taschenfederkern) and a loosening layer.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong to such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut) will be suitable for non-positioning slatted slats with 14 to 18 slats, but slats with a larger number of slats, 28 or more, will always pay off, where the slats are doubled in the lumbar area and their rigidity is possible regulate.
Mattresses with a spring frame do not belong to the positioning slatted frames, because they do not react to positioning.
In addition to setting the stiffness of the slats, you can also treat yourself to a so-called shoulder cradle.
It is a special attachment of the slats, which allows you to push or even tilt the slat so that the arm of the sleeper &quot;sinks&quot; nicely.
For men who have &quot;shoulders across their backs&quot;, definitely an important thing.
Even mattress manufacturers remember it, who in the &quot;men&#39;s&quot; started using the softening zone in the shoulder area.
They also remember women - they give them a softer surface at the hips.
Aileron or plate gratings with so-called multi-torso suspension are intended for the most demanding customers.
The pressure is distributed to multiple points and the stress is reduced.
However, be careful, once you use the wrong pillow (big and &quot;puffy&quot;) on the right mattress and slat, most of the &quot;plus&quot; will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the tips should only reach the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
A suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, which is preferred, for example, in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should level (along with the shoulder cradle of the grate or the softened zone in the mattress) the height of the shoulder.
Modern mattresses have something in common with the original grass-filled straw beds.
Their manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least additives.
The trend is simply also for organic mattresses.
Crude oil from which polyurethane foams are made are being replaced by natural oils such as castor oil and soybeans.
Soy is probably used by all well-known producers.
&quot;Organic mattresses mean that the core is made of a material of purely natural origin,&quot; explains Petr Vašíček from Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the production of mattress covers, one of the first being aloe vera.
But you can also indulge in microcapsules to release the fresh scent of forest or lavender.
There is also a division for men and women.
While men are &quot;cooled&quot; by the birch plant extract so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, while women are &quot;heated&quot; by the covers.
Red pepper extract increases blood circulation, so it is warmer for the weaker sex.
Today&#39;s favorites?
Mattress made of cold foam (it has larger pores with a broken cell structure, it is more breathable than ordinary polyurethane and also offers better elasticity.
The combination of different stiffnesses of cold foams and &quot;lazy&quot; foam creates multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels should be.
You will pay for a quality mattress from seven thousand crowns and up.
Those that meet health parameters tend to have a lower VAT rate, they are considered medical devices.
Gumotex was the first in the Czech Republic to achieve this advantage.
Saving on the mattress and grate is not easy.
Sometimes it is possible to use, for example, the actions of manufacturers or retailers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers a Duofreeze mattress with Memory foam sewn into the cover for 11,990 crowns.
However, the second one can be purchased for free.
The era of lazy or viscoelastic foams with an open cell structure and high density was started at a &quot;cosmic&quot; pace by the Tempur material.
It was originally created as material for NASA, because astronauts were exposed to enormous congestion during launches.
Tempur softens in the heat, but strengthens in the cold.
It thus adapts perfectly to the warm human body and optimally distributes its pressure.
It is therefore ideal against bedsores, but also to increase sleeping comfort.
Viscoelastic foams are used not only for mattresses, but also for medical products, such as special pillows under the feet, which lighten the legs and venous system.
Domestic manufacturers use, for example, Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents want devices to monitor people, so they want to look after their children
Fear of one&#39;s own child leads more and more people to the idea of babysitting via GPS.
The system, originally created for searching for cars, can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help, for example, in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is still about the size of a matchbox, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Anička and began to look for means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading their privacy.
&quot;We try to tell everyone that this is not a spy, but another means of reducing the likelihood of a tragedy,&quot; says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance equipment to the Czech market.
&quot;I admit that in some cases, such devices can be misused, for example, if they are put in the bag by someone who does not know about it, but we have not yet encountered such a case.&quot;
&quot;Mostly customers actually buy it for security reasons,&quot; Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the &quot;box&quot; serves and how it is used in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child does not want to wear anything like this, they will simply get rid of it.
&quot;Even very young children show great creativity in how to intentionally lose some things when they don&#39;t want to be in control.&quot;
