A longer index finger than a ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have an index finger longer than a ring finger are at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Cancer Magazine.
This may be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
&quot;Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men under 60,&quot; said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors, such as family health burden, Eeles added.
Between 1994 and 2009, she and colleagues in Britain followed more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and over 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had their index finger on their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
However, in the case of those who had their index fingers longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, for men under the age of 60, the decline was as much as 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers - formed during the prenatal period - seems to reflect the different levels of sex hormones to which the baby is exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone supports growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he was briefly aware of this study, but it did not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer was &quot;completely proven&quot;.
