Arsenic-resistant microbes increase the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the space for new life forms on Earth and possibly beyond.
Researchers have discovered an unusual bacterium here on Earth, claiming that it is a sign that life has possibilities that go beyond the main elements that have been considered and fundamental so far.
&quot;This organism has a dual ability.&quot;
&quot;It can grow with either phosphorus or arsenic.&quot;
&quot;This fact is very strange, but it is not proof that it is a form of truly &#39;extraterrestrial&#39; life,&quot; commented Paul CW Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of a report that appeared in an online issue of Science on Thursday.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, the researchers found that the bacteria, discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
&quot;You&#39;ll be amazed at what else is possible,&quot; said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
This finding is important for the search for life outside of Earth, because researchers must be able to recognize life and know what life might look like, Anbar said.
The study focuses on microbes found on Earth.
However, a report on the news published for discussion, which did not reveal the details of the finding, has sparked widespread speculation on the Internet that the report reveals the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery &quot;shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider &#39;standard&#39; may not be so absolutely necessary for life,&quot; explained Charles Cockell, a professor at Planetary and Space Sciences Research. Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
&quot;This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element by another in basic biochemistry and biochemical structure,&quot; Cockell added.
It was not an accidental finding.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA&#39;s Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because of its high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that a microbe that is exposed to both elements may be able to replace each other.
&quot;Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;As a result, it is very difficult for organisms to separate these elements from each other.&quot;
&quot;However, arsenic is so different that it doesn&#39;t work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes,&quot; Anbar explained.
The researchers collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which the bacteria are able to adapt to and grow.
Microbes grow better when exposed to phosphorus, but since they can also survive with arsenic replacement, there is an increased possibility that an arsenic-using life form may occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by phosphorus, was not new, but there was never an example of this.
Arsenic was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could be used by earlier life forms.
&quot;This suggests that there may have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early days of the Earth,&quot; said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon&#39;s research team.
