And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be like, which runs into the idea of following old traditions, which is held by a large part of other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong eurozone, which would include Germany, but also, for example, Austria and the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is a return to March - although now it may seem like a scifi, this version has widespread public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option, according to the German proposals, is to revise the euro with greater macroeconomic surveillance, budgetary rigor, fines for the offending states, possible deferrals of payments for some of them, and extending the possible costs of regulation to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no room for dials now.
