The second was shown by this Central European country, when Merkel painfully dragged out the decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism at the time, but the truth is that political consensus in Germany and public opinion, which was also published, were strongly opposed to saving Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel reappeared with a clear position, calling for the European Union conventions to be reformed so as to allow a Member State to be rescued and at the same time to allow private creditors to bear part of the costs.
This view was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, albeit in a somewhat relaxed form, has been approved, and we should follow the Union&#39;s reform process in the coming months, which should enable these measures from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it tells us all that, although measures need to be taken now, with which it seems to disagree too much, the old functioning of the euro will come to an end from that date.
2013 will mark the birth of a new currency zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely sanctioned and may be forced to announce deferral of payments, and the private sector will also have to bear part of the cost.
Germany suggests that we must take a strict path of growth with increased savings and investment, moderate consumption, improved productivity and competitiveness, and capital buffers.
They simply do not intend to tolerate another option based on receivables and building, with huge balance of payments gaps that prevailed in the years of Spain&#39;s growth boom.
The offer is clear.
And we would be wrong if we didn&#39;t understand.
It is not just a matter of restoring the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they want from us is much harder.
And the worst part is that under these conditions, we could be wrong about ourselves.
I hope that these current turbulences will be replaced by greater calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities they give us until the spring of 2013.
Prime Minister Zapatero also seems to understand this, and his double statement (reforms promised after meeting with big business last Saturday and yesterday&#39;s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism from Merkel, the idea has opened up that things need to be put in place. all right.
However, the red line that Germany has drawn is here, and it does not seem to want to move with it.
And leaving a eurozone full of not-so-serious countries cannot be ruled out from the possibilities that can be considered.
Well, Germany will always be able to tell us that it has warned us.
Sport and circumvention rules
The tricks shown by Alonso and Ramos in the match with Ajax show wit, not the intention to escape punishment.
The alleged exclusions of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Champions League match against Ajax on 23 November have led to a sea of ink being written about whether or not this is unsportsmanlike conduct and whether UEFA might not have both footballers. punish.
As is well known, a few minutes before the end of the match (which their team had clearly won), the players named deliberately wasted time one by one at the time of the foul to provoke the referee, who showed them a second yellow card.
