In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Board sentenced José Mourinho to two matches and the offenders were fined.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is not a new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, ie rules that are unwritten but followed.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that it was attended by the Real Madrid team (which boasts nobility and honor in its anthem and which has already fined its players for similar acts) and, apparently, the dramatization led by Mourinho, who thus adding another episode to his comedian and provocateur&#39;s long history.
in any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of conduct, which is not explicitly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, ie whether these acts circumvent the law; these are indeed actions that respect sporting rules, but they seem to be trying to circumvent their meaning.
It deals with the type of damage such actions affect the sporting spirit.
One of the requirements of sports behavior is the physical inviolability of opponents, which was not violated in these cases, ie there was no violent game.
Another of these essentials of a clean game is to avoid that players have an advantage over the opponent&#39;s team due to their offense - which has not happened here either.
So paradoxical about the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as deception or circumvention of the law did not happen, there was no covert violation of the rules to avoid sanction, but this behavior was to be as obvious as possible in order to receive punishment.
They waited and gladly received punishment.
Another question, however, is what advantage the perpetrators will benefit from their intentional offense.
Here it is necessary to state that the opponent does not get into a disadvantaged position, and that there will be no benefit in the current match, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage obviously is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could jeopardize their participation in a future match.
However, this is an advantage from a long-term perspective and with a certain degree of uncertainty, so at first glance the team can be eliminated, and in addition, by doing so, players will be penalized and move to the second round of cards, in which one card less than round one.
So as the rounds continue, it will not be entirely clear whether this is an advantage.
In short and well, these negotiations do not go against the sporting spirit, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow you to get the most out of the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, the players did not aim to avoid being penalized (which would be a clear case of circumventing the rules), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made strategic decisions without avoiding or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between wit and circumvention is not entirely clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the instructions for provoking them were transmitted from management.
Damage to sports principles by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
