The United States is changing the rules for issuing visas
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Service Centers before being interviewed at the Consular Section; costs will be lower and waiting times will be reduced.
From January 10, 2011, the visa negotiation process at the US Embassy and consulates will change.
with the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centers (ASC) before being interviewed by the Consular Section.
The ASC staff will take the applicant&#39;s biometric information and this will be assessed by the Consular Section before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, you will no longer have to pay a fee for arranging a meeting, the second for processing the application and another for delivering the document by the transport service.
The applicant pays only one fee, which covers all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: an amount equivalent to $ 140 for a tourist visa, $ 150 for visas with an application (including visas for temporary workers) and $ 390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to interview the consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC to present their documents and have their fingerprints taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be collected at the ASC, applicants who require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Section will spend less time there than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra $ 26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application process, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
