World Plan for Lighting Restoration
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancún a plan to restore home lighting, shop lighting and industrial space in 100 countries to reduce the greenhouse effect (GES), which is close to one-third of the further reduction needed to stabilize the planet&#39;s climate from now until 2020. ..
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN wants to push through in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-implement reduction commitments on the part of industrialized countries.
According to yesterday&#39;s plan, if incandescent bulbs, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, are replaced by fluorescent light bulbs or, even better, light bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or &quot;LED&quot; in English), a substantial amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt ) GES emissions from the planet due to lighting would be eliminated.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the world&#39;s car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with significant emissions, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have joined voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But another 5 Gt will have to be deducted from this balance in order to stabilize the climate heating at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to rule out getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, ie 5%, is the product of light.
With fluff compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, and with new bulbs with DEL, we reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluorescent light bulbs last on average from 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL bulbs, launched by Philips this week - the company reportedly participated in a UN study - have an expected lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a glowing bulb, giving us an idea of the potential savings. with a compensation plan that would apply in 100 countries.
All of these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit less heat.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection points.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a light-compact light bulb, but rather thermal coal-fired power plants, which emit much of the mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these headquarters circulate 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also details the benefits that each country would make from this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $ 1 billion a year on electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 billion power plants, which would cost $ 2.5 billion to build.
