Climate: how France hacked its promises of funding
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to test keeping on the promises of fast-unlocked funding (called fast start or early funding), implemented by developed countries.
And big French hacks have been uncovered
Under the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged $ 30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has pledged € 7.2 billion over three years and France € 1.26 billion (ie € 420 million a year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU took a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: a report detailing its Member States&#39; event, a press conference, a grand side event, brochure distribution ...
A transparent operation invaluable and valued at its true value: developed countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it has released € 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to deliver on its € 7.2 billion pledge in 2012.
But if we focus on the detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Accord, these funds are &quot;new and additional&quot; to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to State Aid for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what is meant by &quot;new and additional&quot;.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been maintained and it is adding 150 million to the three-year fast start funding title.
Other countries have chosen similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
By contrast, France considers that the funding of &quot;all new projects&quot; in 2010 is &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, there is no reference to previous period expenditure or to the global level of Public Aid for Development d&#39;Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of France&#39;s support to developing countries may remain unchanged (or even reduced), it has to honor its commitment to finance &quot;new and additional&quot; ...
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that € 1 borrowed equals € 1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be demonstrated for some investments that are profitable (often emission reduction projects based on more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present the one euro we get as equivalent to the one euro we give ..., they should not We would understand it by virtue of its liabilities, but as the price of the loan to the creditor country (ie the equivalent interest rate).
But France can only give such a justification: it &quot;keeps&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros, of which 91.5% is a loan (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) - see document EU so you can verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use a loan on such a scale.
Germany has demanded 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) are keeping their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union gives € 1 in fulfillment of its promise, France will give only 10 centimes and considers this effort to be comparable.
A beautiful piece of juggling!
In summary, in its &quot;fast start&quot; financing, France operates with a double shading: on the one hand with the development of the stock over time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it spends only 36.1 million euros, it can be convinced that it is spending 420 million euros &quot;new and additional&quot; in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it was Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate if they only borrow?) And in negotiations, because development countries are not completely naive ...
The chapter on early financing is only a small issue, relatively short-lived, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in a huge machine like the UNFCCC.
Let&#39;s hope that&#39;s not our case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France should announce a change in its way of keeping the accounts for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of respecting its obligations and of decency and fairness towards the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France should avoid discussing deposits in long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): we will not escape the question of &quot;additionality&quot; or how to account for loans.
France should change its position to make it as progressive on these deposits as it is on others.
So everyone has hopes for the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will be coming to Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement of France&#39;s fast start and its vision of &quot;additionality&quot; and the use of loans could trigger the increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
A warning about pesticides that children eat.
One day, a ten-year-old child will see 81 different chemicals, according to a study published this Wednesday, from the Future Generations Association (ex- Movement for Rights and Preservation of Future Generations).
The association, which points out that its results &quot;do not have significant statistical value due to the low number of analyzed samples, but are characteristic of the processed issues&quot;, bought food normally consumed in four meals and one snack as a light snack per child between July and September. about ten years in supermarkets in l&#39;Oise and Paris.
These typical dishes, including official recommendations - five pieces of fresh fruit and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day - as well as confectionery, were analyzed by research laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are carcinogenic, possible or probable, and five are clear carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that could act as interferers for endocrine (PE) glands. , according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
&quot;Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we see well in our research that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants, possibly carcinogens, and / or PE is striking,&quot; the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain about ten residues with possible carcinogenic effects and three proven to be certain carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that could disrupt the hormonal system.
An apple imported from Brazil, reported in the study as a small snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same is true for green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, for which studies have found traces of strong insecticides banned in the EU.
In addition, minced meat steak, canned tuna, and even buns and chewing gum were riddled with pesticides and other chemicals.
Analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform in tap water.
Salmon steak for dinner was &quot;the richest&quot; with 34 chemical residues discovered, and even analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave did not avoid analysis.
The ultimate risk for consumers of this &quot;cocktail of contaminants&quot; is likely to be underestimated, &quot;the study said.
Ecological Europe-Greens (EE-LV) has proposed &quot;in the face of an emergency&quot; to establish a moratorium on pesticide use in order to stop the &quot;rise of diseases of civilization&quot;.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) examined the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 were in cereals.